360","20 September 1357":"20 September 1357","1329":"1329","1339":"1339","1416":"1416","Waddenhall, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Waddenhall, Waltham, Kent, England":"Waltham, Kent, England","Petham, Kent, England":"Petham, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Haute","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: nickname or status name from an argot word (thieves’ slang) in Bavaria and Austria for a peasant farmer (see   Hotz   1). Compare   Houts   and   Houtz  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Houtz","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Hautz  ."]},{"name":"Hotz","meanings":["South German and Swiss German: from thieves' cant for a peasant or farmer, which in turn derives from an ancient Germanic personal name, <i>Hugizo</i> or <i>Huzo</i>, pet forms of a compound name formed with <i>hug-</i> as the first element (see, for example,   Hubert  ,   Hugh  ).","South German: possibly a nickname from Middle High German <i>hotzen</i> ‘to run swiftly’."]}]},{"name":"Edmund","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protector’. It was borne by several early royal and saintly figures, including a 9th-century king of East Anglia killed by invading Danes, allegedly for his adherence to Christianity. In the 16th and 17th centuries, there was a good deal of interchange between <i>Edmund</i> and <i>Edward</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Edmund Haute was born before 1329, his father, Henry Haute, was 29 and his mother, Annabell atte Halle, was 18. He married Benedicta De Shelving about 1369, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died about 1360."},"et":{"Bef 1329–Abt 1360":"enne 1329–umbes 1360","1329–1360":"1329–1360","1340–1391":"1340–1391","1353–Male":"1353–Surnud","1357